        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I find what percentage one number is of another?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "To find what percentage X is of Y, divide X by Y and multiply by 100. For example, 40 is what percent of 200? → (40 ÷ 200) × 100 = 20%. Use the \"X is what % of Y?\" module above to solve this in one click." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I calculate a percentage increase or decrease?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Percentage change = [(New Value − Old Value) ÷ Old Value] × 100. If the result is positive, it's an increase; if negative, it's a decrease. For example, a price going from ₹400 to ₹500 is a 25% increase. Use the Percentage Change Calculator on this page to get the result instantly." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I find the new value after a percentage increase or decrease?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Multiply the original value by (1 + percentage/100) for an increase, or (1 − percentage/100) for a decrease. For example, a 10% increase on 200 → 200 × 1.10 = 220. Use Mode B of the Percentage Change Calculator above — enter the original value and the percentage, and it does the rest." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does the discount calculator work?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The discount calculator finds the final price after applying a percentage off. Enter the original price and the discount percentage, and it instantly shows you the discounted price and how much you save. For example, 30% off ₹1,000 = final price of ₹700, saving you ₹300." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I calculate a tip using the tip calculator?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Enter your total bill amount and the tip percentage you want to leave (e.g. 10%, 15%, or 20%). The tip calculator instantly shows the tip amount and the final total you need to pay. For example, a 15% tip on a ₹800 bill = ₹120 tip, making the total ₹920." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the basic percentage formula?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The basic percentage formula is: Percentage = (Part ÷ Whole) × 100. This formula is the foundation for all percentage calculations — whether you're finding a discount, calculating exam scores, or comparing two values. All modules on this calculator are built on this formula." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I use this calculator for exam marks and grades?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — the percentage calculator is widely used by students to calculate their percentage of marks obtained. Simply enter your total marks scored as the \"Part\" and the maximum marks as the \"Whole\". For example, scoring 450 out of 500 → (450 ÷ 500) × 100 = 90%." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is this percentage calculator free and accurate?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, this tool is completely free with no signup required. All calculations run directly in your browser — no data is sent to any server. The results are mathematically precise, making it reliable for academic, financial, and everyday use." }
        }
      ]
    }</script>
  </Fragment>
</Layout>
